<div id="main_content">
	<h2>Mom's Battle With Cancer Inspires UCF Graduate to Pursue Career in Medicine</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Courtney Gilmartin
		
		<span class="date">July 30, 2008</span></p>
	
	
	
		<div class="article_img" style="width: 226px;">

			<img alt="Article Main Picture" src="http://news.ucf.edu/resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/1000/NE1514/en_US/pullen main.jpg" height="345" width="226"  /> 
			
				<p class="photo_credit">Photo: Jacque Brund</p>
			
			<p>Sarah Pullen was chosen this month as UCF's third Jack Kent Cooke Scholarship winner in the past four years. She will start medical school in the fall. </p>
			
				<p class="note"><a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=00240041b3258d8011b74415fa500b44">Full Photo</a></p>
			
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
		</div>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:cdellert@mail.ucf.edu">Christine Dellert, News & Information</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-2947</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.jackkentcookefoundation.org">Jack Kent Cooke Foundation</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>Watching her single mom fight a losing battle against cancer -- and a &ldquo;fragmented and inefficient&rdquo; health care system -- could have ruined Sarah Pullen&rsquo;s spirit.</p>
<p>Instead, Pullen grew determined to become what her mom never had -- a family doctor who focused on patient relationships as well as diseases.</p>
<p>Pullen, of Tallahassee, was chosen this month as the University of Central Florida&rsquo;s third Jack Kent Cooke Scholarship winner in the past four years. She will put her award of up to $50,000 toward her studies at the University of South Florida&rsquo;s College of Medicine.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The medical profession is about healing people, but now it seems the person has been lost,&rdquo; said Pullen, whose mom, Sheryl, died in 2007. &ldquo;Every patient is a person, not a disease or a set of symptoms.&rdquo;</p>
<p>One of the largest and most competitive scholarship programs in the nation, the Jack Kent Cooke Foundation Graduate Scholarship provides awards of up to $50,000 a year for up to six years of study to deserving low-income college seniors and recent college graduates. About 50 of 1,000 students nominated for scholarships each year receive them.</p>
<p>Pullen, a National Merit Scholar, graduated in May with a Bachelor of Science in Molecular and Microbiology. She also was enrolled at UCF&rsquo;s Burnett Honors College.</p>
<p>Pullen&rsquo;s mom&rsquo;s health deteriorated while she was at UCF, and she no longer could work. The financial strain on the family eventually led to bankruptcy. But Sarah Pullen did not let her family&rsquo;s health and financial struggles affect her education.</p>
<p>&ldquo;She never missed labs. She never missed classes. She maintained her composure, and she never sought out any special attention,&rdquo; said Alvin Wang, dean of the Burnett Honors College. &ldquo;She has this very strong, very quiet determination, and despite the emotional turmoil, she was able to persevere and get beyond that difficult time in her life and excel.&rdquo;</p>
<p>At UCF, Pullen volunteered at local elementary schools as part of a UCF-Junior Achievement partnership and worked as a research assistant with Biomedical Sciences faculty member Cristina Fernandez-Valle. She also was president of the Golden Key International Honour Society and inducted into Phi Kappa Phi Honor Society.</p>
<p>Pullen&rsquo;s long-term goal is to open a free or walk-in clinic so she can help patients who cannot otherwise afford health care.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Becoming a doctor is hard, but being a doctor is even harder,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;Nevertheless, there is nothing else I would rather do. I want to be the smile and open ear, offering hope and compassion. I want to learn about this incredible construct -- the body. I want to listen, to care, and, most of all, to heal.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Pullen will be honored at the Jack Kent Cooke Foundation&rsquo;s Scholars Weekend in August at Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore. Scholars will participate in activities related to academic subjects, current events, the arts, and personal growth.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Founded in 2000, the Jack Kent Cooke Foundation is a private and independent foundation established by the estate of Jack Kent Cooke to help young people of exceptional promise reach their full potential through education.</p>
<p>The scholarship recipients will pursue graduate studies in many fields, including medicine, law, theology and education.&nbsp; <br />
For more information on the Jack Kent Cooke Foundation, visit <a href="http://www.jackkentcookefoundation.org">www.jackkentcookefoundation.org</a>.<br />
&nbsp;</p>
<hr />
<p><b>UCF Stands For Opportunity: </b>The University of Central Florida is a metropolitan research university that ranks as the 6th largest in the nation with more than 48,000 students. UCF's first classes were offered in 1968. The university offers impressive academic and research environments that power the region's economic development. UCF's culture of opportunity is driven by our diversity, Orlando environment, history of entrepreneurship and our youth, relevance and energy. For more information visit <a href="index.html">http://news.ucf.edu</a>.</p>
		
	
